ntral to the kidneys and partialy enveloping the anterior gonads in Elasmobranchii. Apparently important to the immune system.\" [http://www.fishbase.org/glossary/Glossary.php?q=epigonal+organ]\nsynonym: \"subgonal organ\" EXACT []\nis_a: UBERON:0004177 ! hemopoietic organ\nrelationship: composed_primarily_of CL:0000738 {source=\"Honma1983\"} ! leukocyte\nrelationship: contains_process GO:0030097 ! hemopoiesis\nrelationship: in_lateral_side_of UBERON:0000468 ! multicellular organism\nrelationship: in_taxon NCBITaxon:7778 {source=\"Wikipedia\"} ! Elasmobranchii\nrelationship: never_in_taxon NCBITaxon:7863 {source=\"Wikipedia\"} ! Holocephali\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0002390 ! hematopoietic system\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0002405 ! immune system\nrelationship: surrounds UBERON:0000991 ! gonad\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010054\nname: malleus cartilage element\ndef: \"A malleus endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.\" [OBOL:automatic]\nxref: EMAPA:18229\nintersection_of: UBERON:0015018 ! malleus endochondral element\nintersection_of: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0002418 ! cartilage tissue\nrelationship: develops_from UBERON:0006262 ! malleus pre-cartilage condensation\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010055\nname: stapes cartilage element\ndef: \"A stapes endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.\" [OBOL:automatic]\nxref: EMAPA:18230\nis_a: UBERON:0011607 {source=\"http://people.eku.edu/ritchisong/342notes4.htm\"} ! hyomandibular cartilage\nintersection_of: UBERON:0015016 ! stapes endochondral element\nintersection_of: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0002418 ! cartilage tissue\nrelationship: develops_from UBERON:0006294 ! stapes pre-cartilage condensation\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0001686 ! auditory ossicle bone\nproperty_value: editor_note \"TODO - check relationship to Recihert's\" xsd:string\nproperty_value: taxon_notes \"The stapes is homologous to the hyomandibula. In this ontology, we use the class 'hyomandibular cartilage' generally to include the future stapes, the future hyomandibular bone of teleosts and the unossified cartilage in sharks.\" xsd:string\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010074\nname: chromaffin system\ndef: \"Organ system subdivision that consists primarily of chromaffin cells and their supporting structures.\" [http://orcid.org/0000-0002-6601-2165]\nsynonym: \"argentaffin system\" RELATED [MESH:A06.224]\nsynonym: \"chromaffin tissue\" RELATED []\nxref: FMA:79645\nxref: MESH:D002838\nis_a: UBERON:0011216 ! organ system subdivision\nrelationship: composed_primarily_of CL:0000166 ! chromaffin cell\nrelationship: develops_from UBERON:0002342 {source=\"CL\", source=\"ISBN:0073040584\"} ! neural crest\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0000949 {source=\"cjm\"} ! endocrine system\nproperty_value: taxon_notes \"in adult cylostomes and teleosts, the interrenal bodies are separate from chromaffin bodies\" xsd:string\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010129\nname: femur cartilage element\ndef: \"A femur endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.\" [OBOL:automatic]\nsynonym: \"femoral cartilage condensation\" EXACT [EMAPA:17742]\nxref: EMAPA:17742\nis_a: UBERON:0005863 ! cartilaginous condensation\nintersection_of: UBERON:0015052 ! femur endochondral element\nintersection_of: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0002418 ! cartilage tissue\nrelationship: develops_from UBERON:0006234 ! femur pre-cartilage condensation\nrelationship: has_potential_to_develop_into UBERON:0000981 ! femur\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0005254 {source=\"EMAPA\"} ! upper leg mesenchyme\nproperty_value: editor_note \"TODO - request EHDAA2\" xsd:string\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010164\nname: collection of hairs\ndef: \"An anatomical cluster that composed_primarily_of a strand of hair.\" [OBOL:automatic]\nsynonym: \"hairs\" EXACT [FMA:70752]\nsynonym: \"hairs set\" EXACT [FMA:70752]\nsynonym: \"pili\" EXACT OMO:0003011 [FMA:TA]\nsynonym: \"set of hairs\" EXACT [FMA:70752]\nxref: FMA:70752\nintersection_of: UBERON:0034925 ! anatomical collection\nintersection_of: has_member UBERON:0001037 ! strand of hair\nrelationship: has_quality PATO:0010001 ! disconnected\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010212\nname: laryngeal apparatus\ndef: \"Apparatus located between the lungs and the buccal cavity. This apparatus is composed of a pair of arytenoid cartilages that are supported by the cricoid ring.\" [AAO:0000267]\nsynonym: \"laryngeal cartilage system\" EXACT [EHDAA2:0000904]\nxref: AAO:0000267\nxref: EHDAA2:0000904\nis_a: UBERON:0034921 ! multi organ part structure\nrelationship: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0001739 ! laryngeal cartilage\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0001737 {source=\"EHDAA2\"} ! larynx\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0008895 ! splanchnocranium\nproperty_value: editor_note \"check this. See also https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/wiki/The-axial-skeleton\" xsd:string\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010349\nname: otic capsule pre-cartilage condensation\ndef: \"An otic capsule endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.\" [OBOL:automatic]\nsynonym: \"otic capsule anlage\" EXACT []\nxref: EHDAA2:0000833\nintersection_of: UBERON:0004637 ! otic capsule\nintersection_of: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0005866 ! pre-cartilage condensation\nrelationship: part_of UBERON:0003110 ! otic region\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010362\nname: endoskeleton\ndef: \"Skeletal subdivision that undergoes indirect development and includes elements that develop as a replacement or substitution of other elements or tissues.\" [GO_REF:0000034, http://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0051070, PSPUB:0000170, VSAO:0000037]\nsynonym: \"replacement skeleton\" EXACT [VSAO:curator]\nxref: VSAO:0000037\nxref: Wikipedia:Endoskeleton\nxref: XAO:0004026\nis_a: UBERON:0010912 {source=\"VSAO\"} ! subdivision of skeleton\nrelationship: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0010522 ! replacement element\nrelationship: in_taxon NCBITaxon:7742 ! Vertebrata <vertebrates>\nproperty_value: external_definition \"An endoskeleton is an internal support structure of an animal, composed of mineralized tissue. Endoskeleton develops within the skin or in the deeper body tissues. The vertebrate is basically an endoskeleton made up of two types of tissues (bone and cartilage). During early embryonic development the endoskeleton is composed of notochord and cartilage. The notochord in most vertebrates is replaced by vertebral column and cartilage is replaced by bone in most adults. In three phyla and one subclass of animals, endoskeletons of various complexity are found: Chordata, Echinodermata, Porifera, and Coleoidea. An endoskeleton may function purely for support (as in the case of sponges), but often serves as an attachment site for muscle and a mechanism for transmitting muscular forces. A true endoskeleton is derived from mesodermal tissue. Such a skeleton is present in echinoderms and chordates. The poriferan 'skeleton' consists of microscopic calcareous or siliceous spicules or a spongin network. The Coleoidae do not have a true endoskeleton in the evolutionary sense; here, a mollusk exoskeleton evolved into several sorts of internal structure, the 'cuttlebone' of cuttlefish being the best-known version. Yet they do have cartilaginous tissue in their body, even if it is not mineralized, especially in the head, where it forms a primitive cranium. The endoskeleton gives shape,support and protection to the body and provides a mean of locomotion.[Wikipedia:Endoskeleton]t\" xsd:string {source=\"Wikipedia:Endoskeleton\"}\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010371\nname: ecto-epithelium\ndef: \"Epithelium composed of cells that develops from the ectoderm[FMA,modified].\" [FMA:69064]\nsynonym: \"ectoderm-derived epithelium\" EXACT []\nxref: FMA:69064\nintersection_of: UBERON:0000483 ! epithelium\nintersection_of: develops_from UBERON:0000924 ! ectoderm\nrelationship: composed_primarily_of CL:0002077 ! ecto-epithelial cell\n\n[Term]\nid: UBERON:0010394\nname: lymphocyte domain\ninte